thomas j mcgrath a lawyer in new york who serves as the 
secretary of the american austrian foundation said wednesday that 
mrs bloch resigned because she found the controversy surrounding 
her husband hurt her effectiveness on the job 
the board has decided to close its office in washington and move 
its headquarters from washington to new york the group is looking 
for a successor to mrs bloch who resigned tuesday 
felix bloch the former no 2 official at the us embassy in 
vienna and a veteran of 30 years in the foreign service has been 
under surveillance by fbi agents since june 
just imagine the terrible pressure and the problem mrs bloch 
is having mcgrath said im sure every time she turns around 
they say oh youre that mans wife 
bloch has denied any wrongdoing and no charges have been filed 
against him 
a secretary at the american austrian foundation said mrs bloch 
was not available for comment and she did not immediately return a 
message left on her home answering machine mcgrath said she has 
relatives in new york she often stays with 
mcgrath said the foundation which received private contributions 
and about 39000 from the austrian foreign ministry in 1988 will 
continue to operate programs such as one that promotes exchanges for 
young journalists 
meantime the fbi refused wednesday to discuss the status of the 
bloch case 
bloch 54 was placed on administrative leave with pay from his 
state department job in june a month before allegations against him 
were made public 
bloch was trailed for weeks by reporters and photographers as he 
went about his business operating from his apartment more recently 
he has disappeared from the media spotlight 
the justice department launched its probe after bloch was 
