<TEXT>
jessye norman who has probably the most lustrous 
female voice in opera today was the guest artist at the opening of 
the new york philharmonics season in avery fisher hall 
she sang gloriously both before and after intermission at the 
concert wednesday night televised by pbs as live from lincoln 
center 
the evening began with music director zubin mehtas remarkable 
conducting of wagners overture to tannhauser it had the pure 
sweet religious faith which is one of the major themes of the opera 
a feeling of cleansing its listeners finally the music swelled 
into an electrifying ending 
mehta certainly has a feel for opera the new york philharmonic 
sounded like one of the great orchestras 
miss norman followed singing mahlers five late songs to poems 
by friedrich ruckert she shaped each of those familiar songs 
differently but with no sense of stretching to be different the 
first was poignant the third sometimes mysterious the third tender 
then swelling to become tones a listener could enter in the final 
song i have withdrawn from the world miss norman used a dark 
lush tone to convey something stark then shaded it into calm 
after intermission she sang the liebestod from wagners 
tristan und isolde even in that outpouring from a woman in a 
trance of love miss norman had nuances she started softly then 
rose to the power of isoldes largerthenlife vision though her 
vocal strength with a largerthanusual orchestra on stage was 
remarkable she lost no tonal beauty 
the orchestra played the prelude to tristan leading up to 
the liebestod 
the other piece on the program was mozarts 40th symphony 
mehta may have been slightly less inspired by that than by the 
operatic pieces balances in the second movement didnt sound just 
right but it is a rather hyper symphony and mehta and the 
philharmonic did capture that 
it was suggested ahead of time to audience members that womens 
gowns be white black or a combination of white and black and most 
women complied miss normans gown in contrast was bright patterns 
which looked inspired by africa or japan a covered walkway and tent 
for a late dinner kept the heavy rain off concertgoers bouquets in 
tall slender silver vases on each table were of white flowers 
