<TEXT>
a proposal to expand the rights of the disabled 
could put such a financial strain on city transit services that it 
ends up harming the general public and the handicapped alike 
congressional critics of the legislation say 
republicans on a house transportation subcommittee questioned 
wednesday whether wheelchair lifts should be required on all public 
transit buses pointing to one major city where existing lifts are 
used only every other day on average 
a bush administration official told the surface transportation 
subcommittee the provision is a key part of the americans with 
disabilities act which has come to be known as civil rights 
legislation for the handicapped 
the universal use of the lifts and a requirement for 
doortodoor bus service for those who cant make it to a bus stop 
would help get the nations 43 million disabled people into the 
mainstream of daily american life said roland j mross deputy 
administrator of the urban mass transportation administration 
republicans on the panel however are questioning the blanket 
nature of the requirements 
im also concerned that if we increase costs to the point that 
we bring a reduction of service then we are not serving the disabled 
and were not serving the general public either said rep bud 
shuster rpa 
each lift adds about 10000 to 15000 to the 155000 cost of a 
bus and adds 2000 to the annual maintenance cost mross told the 
panel he estimated the annual cost just of buying lifts at 30 
million umta would probably pay 24 million of that he said 
although there are already regulations governing access by the 
elderly and handicapped to mass transit receiving federal funds the 
new act would be far stricter 
at issue in wednesdays hearing was a requirement in the bill 
already passed by the senate and endorsed by the bush 
administration that all public transit buses be equipped with 
wheelchair lifts 
shuster said transportation department figures show that in 
seattle which has liftequipped buses each lift is used every 
other day 
spokesman for the seattle and the cambria county pa systems 
which are considered leaders in serving the handicapped told the 
panel the bill would cause hardships 
but ellen daly legislative analyst at the presidents committee 
on employment of people with disabilities said the existing service 
keeps the handicapped virtually confined to their homes 
she said many systems that have doortodoor service for the 
disabled require long advance notice 16 or 17 hours on the average 
and require a large amount of red tape to qualify for the service 
you cant decide on a moments notice that you want to go 
shopping or stay at the office late she said 
the senate passed a version of the bill with the transit 
requirements on sept 7 
