<TEXT>
a survey of 6911 white middleclass college 
students found that they knew how to protect themselves against aids 
and other sexually transmitted diseases but werent doing it 
about 75 percent of the canadian students reported that they were 
sexually active but only 19 percent said they used condoms 
regularly twentysix percent said they never used condoms 
yet 80 percent answered correctly when asked questions about 
preventing sexually transmitted diseases 
the survey suggests most education and media campaigns to 
increase condom use are dismal failures said dr noni macdonald 
of the university of ottawa she presented her findings wednesday at 
a meeting of the american society for microbiology 
macdonald a member of a canadian health ministry task force on 
sexually transmitted diseases said her findings probably would 
apply to white middleclass us college students 
if weve got it in middleamerica canada you must have it in 
middle america she said 
the study found that 30 percent of 14yearolds already had had 
intercourse so had 77 percent of college men and 73 percent of 
college women 
one in four men and one in eight women reported having had at 
least 10 sexual partners 
these findings held true right across the country 
coasttocoast little town big town said macdonald 
a recent study of condom use by adolescent males in the united 
states found that 57 percent reported use of a condom the last time 
they had intercourse but that only 30 percent said they had always 
used a condom 
the author of the american study freya sonenstein of the urban 
institute in washington dc said condom use has increased but 
that condom use is lowest in the adolescents who are most at risk 
either because they have multiple partners or have sex with 
prostitutes for example 
condoms have been widely promoted as a way to cut the risk of 
getting infected with the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv that 
causes aids but they also can protect against other sexually 
transmitted diseases such as chlamydia a common infection that can 
leave women infertile sometimes without causing any symptoms at the 
time of infection 
eight percent of the canadian college students have had at least 
one sexually transmitted disease macdonald said 
sonenstein found that reports of condom use among american 
adolescent males doubled during the past 10 years or so 
dr john moran of the federal centers for disease control said 
condom sales jumped by 20 percent shortly after the us surgeon 
general released his report on aids in 1986 even so syphilis is on 
the rise in inner cities 
it appears obvious to me that there are a lot of people not 
using condoms that should he said in a telephone interview 
clearly there is a large group of people putting themselves at 
risk for hiv by not using condoms 
aids is uncommon among canadian college students now but with 
the rapidity with which theyre having sexual intercourse it would 
not take long to spread macdonald said 
she said that students must be taught not only the facts about 
aids and sexually transmitted diseases but also how to handle 
awkward social and sexual situations so that condom use becomes 
easier 
when you teach someone how to drive a car you dont tell them 
about the engine you teach them how to do it she said 
