<TEXT>
many residents of st simons island never 
lived through a major hurricane but theyre not ignoring the furor 
of hurricane hugo as it headed toward the east coast 
i think anybody is going to be worried its a major 
catastrophic happening said billy cullens a director of the st 
simons chamber of commerce 
at an island grocery store shoppers packed carts with bottled 
water canned goods and other supplies 
compared to past storms theyre taking it more seriously 
supermarket manager richard thomas said a lot more people seem to 
be talking about leaving 
attracted by its beaches golf courses warm climate and southern 
charm about 5000 people have moved to the island 65 miles south of 
savannah since the last hurricane came ashore in georgia in 1979 
st simons is about 10 miles long and is connected to the 
mainland city of brunswick by a sevenmile causeway parts of the 
island remain undeveloped but elsewhere beachfront condos and 
subdivisions have sprouted up amid palms pines and mossdraped oaks 
disaster officials called for the voluntary evacuation of the 
islands 14000 residents late wednesday they were ready to order 
the evacuation of 30000 residents from st simons and lowlying 
areas of brunswick and surrounding glynn county 
we would have to assess the situation look at the tides the 
storm surge and the advice of the national weather service said 
ed stelle the countys community development director 
the weather service issued a hurricane watch wednesday evening 
and said there was an 11 percent chance hugo could come within 65 
miles of savannah between 8 pm today and 8 am friday 
when hurricane david came ashore near savannah on sept 4 1979 
the storm knocked down trees power lines and flooded streets before 
moving into south carolina david left 1200 people dead 19 in the 
united states 
hugo has claimed 25 lives on caribbean islands 
since its last hurricane st simons population jumped from 
9000 
the major problem is the education of people said vernon d 
martin executive director of the coastal georgia regional 
development center in brunswick 
weve got a lot of new people who probably arent familiar with 
coastal problems associated with a hurricane theyre now aware of 
the warnings and what the warnings mean 
the problem is common in georgias eight coastal counties the 
area is the states fastest growing region with the population 
surging from 350000 in 1980 to an estimated 400000 in 1988 growth 
has been spurred by a new submarine base in camden county an army 
division at hinesville an 800millionayear tourist industry and 
an influx of industries 
but cullens said the growth has left the island better equipped 
to withstand hurricanes 
we have a better causeway and a better road system he said 
since hurricane david a twolane causeway with lift bridges has 
been replaced by a fourlane causeway with high bridges the island 
also has strengthened building codes he said 
ann rogers who runs a mailorder business on st simons said 
hugo would be her first hurricane 
i think im more concerned about our business than our house on 
the beach she said wed take our dogs and cats and wed be 
gone 
at the heritage retirement community the staff has met often 
with the elderly residents to prepare them for a possible evacuation 
many of our residents have pets and valuables general 
manager freddie stroud said its hard to explain to them that 
this is a temporary evacuation 
 
