<TEXT>
the environmental protection agencys massive 
annual guide to automobile gas mileage is supposed to tell motorists 
at a glance what cars are the stingiest and the worst guzzlers of 
fuel 
but not always it turns out 
dozens of cars each year are missing from the annual list and 
this year the absent included the entire line of luxury cars from 
mercedesbenz including 11 whose mileage is so poor the cars are 
subject to the special guzzler excise tax 
three of the mercedes cars likely would have made the ten 
worst list had they been included in the epa survey of 981 cars 
that was released earlier this week and widely distributed by the 
news media 
don larson branch manager at the epas auto testing laboratory 
in ann arbor mich said every year perhaps 80 or 90 cars do not 
make the list because manufacturers do not provide the testing data 
to the epa when the mileage guide goes to the printer 
aside from mercedes the epa could not say what specific cars 
were missing a spokesman for general motors corp said gm still 
must submit test data for three cars and industry sources said they 
would not be surprised if a dozen or more other manufacturers had 
yet to submit test information on a few cars each 
there are always a few stragglers said epa spokeswoman 
martha casey 
federal law requires automakers to submit the mileage test data 
and have it certified by the epa before a car is placed on the 
market but they are not required to submit the information by a 
specific date or meet the deadline for the initial industrywide 
mileage guide 
government and industry sources speaking anonymously 
acknowledged the mileage guide can both help and hinder automakers 
manufacturers often test their high mileage cars early to meet the 
deadline for the publication and move more slowly on their 
highmileage models said one official 
the submission of the test data is at the manufacturers 
control i dont know what was in the minds of mercedes in making 
their decision not to submit test results earlier but they do 
have relatively fuel inefficient vehicles said the epas larson 
the deadline for test data this year was aug 30 at the request 
of one automaker it was postponed until sept 5 mercedesbenz 
submitted its first 1990 model test data covering a dozen cars on 
sept 9 said eldert bontekoe of the epas certification office in 
ann arbor 
ab shuman manager of public relations at mercedesbenz of 
north america in montvale nj said in a telephone interview the 
mileage performance of the cars was absolutely not a factor in 
the data being submitted late 
it was just getting it all done said shuman who said the 
company had been unable to complete all the testing in time 
shuman also noted mercedes does not put its 1990 models on the 
market until nov 1 and so has more time to submit the test data 
than many other automakers whose 1990 models hit the showroom in 
september and october 
nevertheless 11 of the mercedes cars showed overall mileage of 
18 miles per gallon or less and are subject to a gas guzzler 
excise tax according to figures provided by the epa 
at least three of the 1990 mercedes models had mileage so low 
they likely would have been among the worst ten in mileage for 
1990 had they been included in the epa survey list 
the mileage data for the mercedes cars along with figures for 
any other cars submitted late will be included in an updated 
mileage list in february 
but ms casey the epa spokeswoman acknowledged the revised list 
usually gets little public attention 
</TEXT>
