<TEXT>
president bush is refusing a request by 
colombian president virgilio barco to reinstate a oneyear colombian 
coffee export that has been beneficial to colombian farmers the 
white house says 
colombias coffee earnings have slumped at the same time that the 
bush administration is seeking barcos help in cracking down on 
cocaine exports 
colombian officials have suggested they will have an even harder 
time persuading hardpressed colombia farmers to grow coffee instead 
of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip 
colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74nation 
international coffee agreement ica to which both the united 
states and colombia belonged collapsed in july after the united 
states pulled out in a dispute over prices with coffeeproducing 
nations 
the agreement set quotas for member nations exports aimed at 
supporting prices of beans at 120 per pound or more some central 
american and others supported by the united states wanted larger 
quotas 
after suspension of the quotas in early july prices fell quickly 
to around 85 cents per pound give or take a few pennies colombia 
has said this will cost 500 million a year in export revenue 
barco whose nation relies on coffee as a major source of export 
earnings had appealed to bush to reconsider the coffee decision and 
to support reinstating the quotas for at least one year 
bush in a letter to barco said the united states was ready to 
negotiate for a new quota system but was unwilling to adhere to the 
nowdefunct agreement presidential press secretary marlin fitzwater 
said wednesday 
