<TEXT>
a special committee today proposed streamlining 
death penalty appeals to assure swifter executions but only after 
guaranteeing condemned prisoners competent legal help 
capital cases should be subject to one complete and fair course 
of collateral review in the state and federal system said the 
panel appointed by chief justice william h rehnquist when this 
review has concluded litigation should end 
retired supreme court justice lewis f powell the committee 
chairman said the current system encourages endless delays 
repetitive appeals and frenzied lastminute activity as death row 
inmates approach scheduled executions 
the hard fact is that the laws of 37 states that have the 
death penalty are not being enforced by the courts powell said 
i respect those who argue for outright abolition of death 
punishment but it seems irrational to retain the penalty and 
frustrate its fair implementation 
powell noted that there are some 2200 death row inmates but 
there have been only 118 executions since the supreme court 
reinstated the death penalty in 1972 
he said the average delay between conviction and execution is 
more than eight years and the longest has been 14 years 
delay of this magnitude is hardly necessary for fairness or for 
thorough review powell said 
the committee he heads recommended that states enact laws to 
assure that death row inmates have adequate legal help throughout 
their appeals at taxpayer expense the committee did not estimate 
the potential cost or the likely reduction in time between 
convictions and executions 
if the state chose not to adopt the plan the current system 
would remain in effect for that state permitting repetitive state 
and federal court appeals 
one feature of the new system would be a sixmonth period to file 
a federal appeal after the prisoner exhausts state appeals there is 
no such time period now 
the current system permits death row inmates to file repeated 
appeals to federal courts to challenge alleged violations of their 
constitutional rights 
under the committees proposal there would be one round of such 
federal appeals unless condemned prisoners could produce new 
evidence to demonstrate innocence 
 
</TEXT>
