<TEXT>
the only known horse ferry left in america 
will be preserved at its underwater location in lake champlain 
where divers will be allowed to examine it and take photographs 
just as were protecting the natural beauty of lake champlain 
what todays event marks is the protecting of the historic 
resources said vermont gov madeleine kunin who dedicated the 
wreck wednesday along with state and local officials historians and 
representatives of the diving community 
the horsepowered ferry which cruised 150 years ago and three 
other shipwrecks are marked with surface buoys and underwater signs 
that encourage divers to look but keep the wreck intact a bright 
yellow sign placed on the horse ferry advises divers to take 
nothing but photos 
the horse ferry or teamboat was powered by two horses or 
mules who walked on a large turntable mounted beneath the deck the 
turntable drove a pair of paddle wheels that allowed the ferry to 
travel the lake between vermont and new york state 
the identity and date of the boat are still unknown but it most 
likely cruised the lake in the first half of the 19th century the 
design is based on an 1819 patent and the vermont legislature 
granted the first teamboat charter on lake champlain in 1821 the 
last teamboat was retired around the time of the civil war 
kevin crisman a marine archaeologist who is documenting the 
wreck said the twohorsepower boat would have been heard several 
miles away with the horses hooves clumping on the deck and the 
iron gears clanking 
today its remains are in 45 feet of water less than a mile 
northwest of the burlington breakwater it is 63 feet long and 23 
feet wide and is extremely fragile said giovanna peebles vermont 
state archaeologist 
divers can see the algaecovered wreck from five to 15 feet away 
crisman said the most spectacular part is the paddle wheels with 
the iron hubs and oak spokes still complete although badly 
deteriorated rising 10 feet above the bottom 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

