children who are hungry sick or homeless are 
poor learners a study by a private educational group said thursday 
calling for greater coordination between schools and social service 
agencies 
the institute for educational leadership inc said the study 
found that changing demographics and lifestyles of american families 
have created problems that schools alone cannot solve 
only 6 percent of families are the socalled traditional ones 
with a breadwinner father housewife mother and two children in 
public schools said the report forty percent of the nations poor 
are children 15 million children are being raised by a single 
parent and 2 million children live with neither parent 
the study entitled the same client the demographics of 
education and service delivery systems said the average income 
for femaleheaded households with children is only 11200 
harold l hodgkinson director of the groups center for 
demographic policy and the author of the report also pointed to 
limited transportation options for the poor such as having to 
travel by bus and subway to get to work day care and school and 
the lack of lowincome housing 8 million lowincome renters 
competing for 4 million housing units as creating great hardships 
particularly for working mothers 
as for health care hodgkinson a former director of the national 
institute of education said 11 percent of americas school children 
are enrolled in special classes for the handicapped roughly 
onethird of these children he said would have a smaller handicap 
or none at all if adequate medical care had been provided during 
pregnancy and in infancy 
it is painfully clear that a hungry sick or homeless child is 
by definition a poor learner yet schools usually have no linkage to 
health or housing organizations outside those run by the schools 
themselves said the report 
at a time when service organizations are increasingly strapped 
financially this kind of interactive organization holds promise 
it may well be that with few increases in funding we could still 
magnify the effectiveness of each dollar several times through 
programs based on interagency collaboration at each governmental 
level 
hodgkinson said that in recent years there has been more 
dialogue among government agencies with the same function but one 
outcome has been organization maintenance not improved services 
for the urgent problems we face this is not enough service 
organizations must begin to see their interdependence across 
functional lines he said 
