under that law for example a single person with 75000 taxable 
income pays a top rate of 33 percent on a 10000 pay raise or 
investment windfall but a 250000ayear earner pays only 28 
percent tax on a similar increase in income 
the democratic plan would apply the 33 percent rate to all 
taxable income above 44900 for a single person and to all above 
74850 for a couple 
assuring that the 33 percent rate would not apply to any 
capitalgains income thus the maximum tax on capital gains which 
for some uppermiddleincome people is 33 percent would be cut to 
28 percent 
rep william h gray iii dpa who as house majority whip is 
the democrats chief votecounter called the proposal a 
continuation of the simplification of the tax code that would 
encourage saving and investment 
rep dan glickman dkan said the plan gives the party a chance 
to stand for something rather than just oppose the capitalgains 
cut the capitalgains reduction has drawn little public response 
he said but the mere mention of iras caused the phone to ring 
rep mike synar dokla calling any capitalgains cut a blow 
against deficit reduction said there would be a large group of us 
that will vote against any kind of change 
i think its a mistake for the democratic party to be 
advocating an increase in taxes until the president has done that 
said rep ed jenkins dga chief sponsor of the capitalgains cut 
that won ways and means approval 
</TEXT>
