<TEXT>
new doubts were raised thursday over prospects 
for the bush administrations strategy to reduce the 13 trillion 
third world debt burden as delegates from 152 nations began arriving 
for talks on global economic issues 
questions about world pollution political upheavals in communist 
eastern europe and china and the roller coaster ride of the us 
dollar were all expected to be addressed during the annual meetings 
of the international monetary fund and the world bank 
but the us debt plan unveiled last march by treasury secretary 
nicholas brady was the major topic on the agenda because resources 
of the imf and world bank are crucial to the success of the effort 
the administration found itself facing new questions about the 
brady plan after three of the largest us banks this week decided 
to set aside more than 4 billion in reserves to cover losses 
related to third world loans 
jp morgan amp co said thursday it was setting aside 2 billion 
to cover loan losses earlier chase manhattan corp the countrys 
third largest bank had said it was setting aside 115 billion and 
manufacturers hanover corp said it was boosting its loan loss 
reserves by 950 million 
the decisions will translate into big thirdquarter losses for 
all three banks 
the increase in loan loss reserves which are expected to be 
followed by other banks came after brazil the third worlds 
largest debtor with 110 billion in loans outstanding missed making 
a 16 billion interest payment this week 
banking analysts cited the brady debt plan as another factor 
driving banks to boost loan reserves under the plan banks are 
encouraged to forgive a portion of their loans to debtor countries 
in exchange for guarantees supplied by the imf and the world bank 
that the remaining debt will be repaid 
thus the brady plan forces the banks to formally acknowledge 
that they will receive less than full repayment on their loans 
executives at both chase and manufacturers hanover cited this as one 
reason for boosting their loss reserves 
last week final agreement on debt reduction terms was reached 
with mexico the first country to qualify for assistance under the 
brady strategy 
some banking analysts said they feared that the actions by major 
banks to boost loan loss reserves could be a signal that these 
institutions would no longer lend new money to third world countries 
paul getman an economist with the wefa group said that so far 
the only bank that is even considering making new loans to mexico is 
citicorp 
robert litan an economist at the brookings institute said the 
question of new money on the part of commercial banks was a concern 
and he said it pointed to the need for a commitment of much greater 
government resources to make the brady plan work 
the bush administration doesnt want taxpayer bailouts for the 
banks and they seem to equate substantial imf and world bank 
guarantees as the equivalent of a taxpayer bailout he said but 
i think you are going to need those kinds of guarantees on both old 
and new debt in order to move the program forward 
a treasury department official praised the decisions to boost 
loan loss reserves as a further move to realism by these 
commercial banks that we welcome and denied that the actions 
represented a threat to continued lending to debtor nations 
by strengthening their financial position banks really have 
more flexibility to participate in a broader range of options 
incluidng debt reduction or debt service reduction and new money 
said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
while both the imf and the world bank are expected to spend 
substantial time discussing the brady debt strategy analysts said 
they expected little to be committed in the way of increased funding 
imf managing director michel camdessus told reporters the mexican 
debt package offered encouragement to other debtor nations to push 
forward with negotiations with their creditor banks 
on the issue of assistance to hungary and poland camdessus told 
reporters that imf officials were holding discussions with officials 
of both countries aimed at providing assistance to support economic 
reforms in eastern europe 
the problems of china were also expected to be taken up at the 
meetings world bank president barber conable told reporters 
wednesday that he hoped to be able to resume lending to china soon 
seven loans totaling nearly 800 million were suspended in june 
following the confrontation between chinese troops and student 
protesters in tiananmen square 
before the opening of the formal sessions of the imf and world 
bank finance officials of the worlds seven richest countries were 
scheduled to hold talks all day saturday to review global economic 
issues 
the closeddoor meeting hosted by brady and federal reserve 
chairman alan greenspan will likely focus on efforts by the rich 
nations to stabilize the value of the dollar which has been rising 
for most of this year despite efforts by the united states and its 
allies to drive it lower 
the rising dollar threatens to derail the administrations effort 
to lower the huge us trade deficit a stronger dollar makes us 
goods less competitive on overseas markets and invites higher 
imports 
