<TEXT>
the fbi said thursday it will not appeal a 
sweeping court order that sets in place mechanisms to end what a 
judge found was systematic discrimination against hispanic agents 
the decision against appealing the may 5 decision by a federal 
judge in texas was made by solicitor general kenneth starr the 
bureau said the fbi made the announcement after receiving word of 
starrs decision 
fbi director william s sessions said in a statement that after 
weighing the myriad legal operational and institutional 
considerations he recommended to the justice department that no 
appeal be pursued in the case 
sessions said the decision not to pursue the appeal is in the 
best interests of fbi employees we must move beyond the frictions 
caused by this case to address the many vital challenges facing the 
fbi in the 1990s 
the court order in the classaction suit by 311 of the bureaus 
approximately 400 hispanic agents directed the fbi to adopt changes 
to end the unsystematic excessively subjective method of 
promoting special agents 
in his order us district judge lucius bunton iii of midland 
texas stripped the special agents in charge of fbi field offices of 
the power to override decisions of career promotion boards 
that system the judge said was anathema to nearly every 
reform advanced by the bureau and ordered by this court to improve 
the fairness and reviewability of promotion decisions 
bunton also appointed an outside panel of three attorneys to 
conduct a casebycase review to determine if as many as 200 
hispanic agents should be promoted to compensate for past 
discrimination 
under the terms of the order the fbi can appeal the panels 
findings to the judge 
buntons order came as a result of more than two years of 
litigation in the classaction case in which he had earlier found 
discrimination against hispanics in promotions and working 
conditions 
the judge had found that hispanic agents were often relegated to 
undesirable assignments such as monitoring the wiretaps of 
spanishspeaking suspects in a criminal investigation 
since taking office in november 1987 sessions conducted a review 
of the fbis personnel and recruitment practices he reorganized the 
bureaus equal employment opportunity office going outside the fbi 
to recruit a manager of that unit who now reports directly to him 
in his order bunton acknowledged that the changes ordered by 
sessions demonstrate energetic and goodfaith effort to correct 
the disparities found by this court 
the suit was filed in early 1987 by bernardo mat perez the 
fbis no 2 agent in el paso the bureaus secondhighest ranking 
hispanic agent after he had suffered a series of demotions 
the judge ordered perez promoted to a job with responsibilities 
commensurate with his experience and training but denied any 
monetary damages or back pay to him or the other plaintiffs who 
eventually joined the lawsuit 
as a result of the court order perez was promoted to deputy 
assistant director of the fbis laboratory division in washington 
the fbi said 
the fbis decision not to appeal was praised by rep don edwards 
dcalif chairman of the house judiciary subcommittee on civil 
rights 
thats exactly the right decision something weve been urging 
for many months edwards said 
its time for them to move on and get at the root causes of the 
problems associated with perez and rochon the congressman said 
referring to a racial harassment suit by a black fbi agent donald 
rochon 
edwards called the rochon case a thorn in their side day after 
day 
rochon accuses the fbi of tolerating racial harassment by white 
agents of him and his family while he was assigned to the chicago 
field office 
the lawsuit also accuses fbi supervisors of retaliating against 
him for complaining of racial harassment 
david kairys rochons lawyer contended in a telephone interview 
this week that the justice department has filed a series of 
frivolous motions that he said were calculated to immobilize 
the court overseeing the case 
