<TEXT>
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
said thursday the dominican republic el salvador and equatorial 
guinea are so far behind in their dues they risk losing their vote 
in the general assembly 
the un charter says any nation two years behind loses the right 
to vote in the assembly 
the assembly may let the country vote if it is satisfied that 
failure to pay is due to circumstances beyond the countrys control 
the dominican republic which is assessed about 224000 
annually must come up with 223600 to keep its voting rights said 
the un chiefs letter 
el salvador assessed more than 74000 annually must pay 
12057 and equatorial guinea assessed the same must pay 46300 
to keep their votes 
when a small impoverished nation has been unable to pay in the 
past its former colonial power or a major ally quietly paid the 
dues 
south africa is also in arrears but has refused to pay since the 
general assembly suspended its voting rights in 1974 as punishment 
for its racial segregation policy if its voting privileges were 
restored south africa would have to pay more than 35 million to 
regain its vote 
dues are based on a formula that largely relies on a nations 
gross national product 
the united states still owes more than anyone as of aug 31 
america was 2788 million in arrears for past years and owes more 
than 216 million for this years dues bringing the total close to 
500 million 
the united states is assessed for onefourth of the regular un 
budget about 216 million a year 
president reagans administration began withholding a large 
portion of the us dues starting in 1985 to spur reforms and budget 
cuts at the world body reagan announced a year ago he was satisfied 
with un progress along these lines and authorized full payment of 
us dues and payment of all back dues on a sixyear plan 
congressional committees refused to pay back dues this year 
citing constraints imposed by the us federal budget deficit 
