<TEXT>
one of the most intimidating threats to peace of 
mind is a congress searching for new sources of revenue because 
somewhere somehow someone will have to pay 
the threat is all the more real because in this if not in other 
matters congress mind seems to be made up never on details 
perhaps but on the general idea that government forever will need 
more money 
in ways most people do not understand proposals for tax cuts 
become tax increases and whenever a tax decrease escapes into law 
it is thereafter stripped of all its benefits leaving little more 
money in taxpayers pockets 
throughout the 1980s tax cuts have been eroded by subsequent 
increases some of them imposed with little publicity why because 
they appeared almost insignificant at the time but as they say 
little increases do add up 
consider the economic recovery tax act of 1981 it promised 
corporate tax reductions averaging 51 billion in the years 198789 
but by 1986 says the tax foundation this reduction became a 
20 billionayear increase 
somehow such things happen when congress goes rummaging through 
the tax code and it may happen again as your neighbors might tell 
you it is one of the most fearsome things that can happen to good 
americans 
the latest tax goround probably was initiated by president bush 
who proposed that capital gains taxes the kind imposed on 
investment earnings be cut substantially from as high as 33 
percent to as low as 15 percent 
to do so he said would raise revenue for a couple of years at 
least because lower taxes would encourage people who owned stocks 
to redeem them for cash and thereby declaring their capital gains 
and paying their taxes 
besides he suggested it was only fair such investments involve 
risk he observed the benefits from such investments are delayed 
rather than immediate and much of the tax is imposed on inflated 
rather than real returns 
some members of congress rebelled saying such a cut would be a 
gift to the rich and could not be permitted the rich should be 
taxed more they said and so they proposed a tax increase which 
congress is now considering 
in such manner has a tax cut generated the threat of a tax 
increase 
seldom however is any tax matter as open clear and 
understandable as that in the past congress has actually passed 
taxes it never meant to pass and has ommitted items it thought it 
had included always there are surprises 
in the recent tax increase proposal for instance the emphasis 
is on making life more expensive for the rich even though the 
definition of rich is highly suspect 
in tax logic for instance a person who never made 20000 a 
year but who through lifelong discipline may be rich for the one 
year in which the funds are redeemed is defined as rich and so 
taxed 
somehow in this latest proposal the matter of private pension 
funds was introduced they have lots of money 2 trillion or more 
so it wasnt askew of tax reasoning to go after them 
and so the suggestion is being made why not tax these taxexempt 
entities every time they are involved in a shortterm securities 
trade 
typically the rationale being offered is not that congress wants 
more money but that those pension funds should be investing for the 
long term too much of america it is said is thinking shortterm 
this will help correct it 
it could do more than that it could become the foot in the door 
or if you prefer the nose of the camel in the tent that is more 
could follow drawn irresistibly by the vast possibilities of such 
vast sums of money 
