ethel flippen was diagnosed with cancer in 
january but a daily 160mile round trip from her home to a hospital 
was daunting and so was the cost of a hotel for the week of 
radiation treatments 
flippen of emporia wasnt the only one faced with the dilemma 
we were having patients call us from out of town saying they 
needed transportation into richmond for their radiation therapy and 
we were finding that these people were coming from long distances on 
a daily basis said norma rawls of the local american cancer 
society 
financially it was hard on them physically it was hard on 
them 
the society turned to the metro richmond hotel and motel 
association which began offering patients free room and board 
about a dozen including flippen have taken advantage of the offer 
since the program began in march 
ive had one patient tell me that she would not have been able 
to get her radiation therapy had it not been for the hotel lodging 
program said rawls this is true of most of these patients 
they could not afford to stay in a hotel monday through friday for 
eight weeks 
flippen who underwent 25 radiation treatments at massey cancer 
clinic of the medical college of virginia hospitals has stayed at 
four of the two dozen participating inns if it hadnt been for 
the hotels and motels i guess i would have just died she said 
to see them come together on something like thisto do 
something good for the community in a very competitive industry is 
something very special said jim b poppell executive director of 
the societys state chapter 
weve talked to a lot of our counterparts across the country 
and we know of no other program where its being made available at 
no cost to patients 
each of the participating hotels agree to provide two weeks of 
complimentary lodging a year referrals come from social workers 
hospitals and oncologists such as dr dean goplerud at the medical 
college of virginia 
the typical patient will have treatments of four or five weeks 
they often feel tired and may suffer a loss of appetite diarrhea 
and nauseau he said the reason they require a place to stay is 
because many of them live a long distance from richmond and have to 
come in every day for treatment they get tired out from the long 
drive 
if free lodging werent available goplerud said hospitalization 
or missing treatments would be the only options for some patients 
