japans trade ministry is considering tax incentives 
for companies that boost imports as a way to correct its 52 billion 
trade surplus with the united states officials said 
we realize that japan accounts for half of the total us trade 
deficit and therefore we are trying to vigorously increase our 
imports yuzuru hatakeyama of the ministry of international trade 
and industry told reporters wednesday 
hatakeyama director general of the international trade policy 
bureau said the ministry is considering a plan to grant special tax 
incentives for importers 
during japans industrial buildup after its defeat in world war 
ii incentives granted to exporters allowed them to reduce their 
taxes by from 1 percent to 3 percent of the value of their exports 
the system was discontinued in 1964 
hatakeyama said the government is considering a similar system to 
promote imports the tax breaks would not extend to importers of raw 
materials he said 
japan is under pressure from the united states to increase its 
imports and institute other economic and trade policy changes to cut 
its surplus 
earlier this month the two countries began a yearlong round of 
bimonthly talks on structural impediments to trade in each nation 
and us officials have said they expect measurable improvement 
in the trade imbalance by next spring 
japan also has been named along with india and brazil as a 
possible target of retaliation under us trade laws for policies 
that allegedly hinder the sale here of supercomputers lumber 
products and satellites 
us commerce secretary robert a mosbacher in a threeday visit 
to japan last week welcomed the idea of tax incentives to japanese 
importers as a farreaching method of increasing imports and cutting 
the trade imbalance 
total japanese imports have risen 165 percent in the first eight 
months of this year and imports from the united states have 
increased by 199 percent from the same period last year the trade 
ministry says 
the senior trade official said the proposed tax breaks are not 
likely to be implemented until next spring at the earliest since 
parliament would have to approve legislation 
but hatakeyama admitted the tax breaks could take even longer 
because of political uncertainties 
plagued by a series of scandals and an unpopular new sales tax 
the governing liberal democratic party lost its majority in the 
upper house of parliament in july for the first time in 34 years 
a general election for the more powerful lower house must be held 
by next summer 
it is not clear whether the proposed tax incentives would be 
legal under rules of the international trade body known as the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade 
but we hope no countries would complain about this scheme 
hatakeyama said 
