<TEXT>
another round of auto plant closings 
is looming for the 1990s but nothing should happen in the next year 
despite an expected drop in vehicle sales a chrysler corp 
executive says 
there absolutely will be more plant closings in the united 
states robert lutz president of chrysler motors corp said 
wednesday if over a period of time market demand is insufficient 
then we would be forced to realign capacity 
lutz president of chryslers vehiclemaking arm predicted that 
142 million vehicles 94 million cars and 48 million light 
trucks will be sold in 1990 that will be down 4 percent to 5 
percent from 1989 sales and 101 percent below the 158 million 
vehicles sold in 1988 the secondbest year in automotive history 
chrysler the no 3 us carmaker closed its kenosha wis 
assembly plant last year last week general motors corp announced 
it would shut its lakewood ga assembly plant in march ford motor 
co hasnt recently announced any plant closings 
over the 90s the market is not going to grow sufficiently to 
absorb all the capacity lutz said 
a large percentage of the new us automaking capacity in recent 
years has come from transplants or foreignbased companies 
operating assembly plants in the united states 
recently nissan motor corp of japan increased capacity at its 
smyrna tenn plant chrysler and mitsubishi motors corp of japan 
began production at their jointventure plant in illinois a 
cooperative venture between gm and suzuki motor co ltd of japan 
opened in canada and hyundai motor co of korea began operating in 
canada 
honda motor co begins production at a second us plant later 
this year in east liberty ohio and isuzu motors ltd and fuji 
heavy industries ltd join together for production later this year 
at lafayette ind all three companies are japanese 
all that adds up to a lot more production capacity for cars and 
trucks 
chrysler is using less than 30 percent of the capacity at its 
bramalea ontario plant but that will rise next year when the 
company begins building a new dodge monaco derived from the eagle 
premier it assembles there now 
on other matters raised wednesday as chrysler wound up its 1990 
model introduction lutz said 
the 2300 whitecollar jobs chrysler tagged for extinction in a 
1 billion costcutting program should be gone by the end of the 
year as expected 
the minivan market segment will continue to grow chryslers 
dominant 56 percent share will slip a little mainly because of the 
entry of new minivans including those from gm and mazda motor corp 
of japan 
chryslers 5 percent average price increase for 1990 cars and 
trucks was due mainly to the companys decision to put driverside 
air bags on all of its usmade cars to meet federal safety 
standards 
