<TEXT>
amerada hess corp has confirmed that its big st 
croix refinery sustained major hurricane damage and will not resume 
full operations for about 60 days 
the company said in a statement after the markets closed 
wednesday that there had been considerable damage to the plant and 
to its administrative buildings and employees housing 
the new york company said the refinery with a capacity of 
545000 barrels a day would resume partial operations in about 30 
days the refinery supplies markets in the eastern united states and 
the gulf of mexico 
reports that there might be major problems at the refinery sent 
gasoline futures surging wednesday on the new york mercantile 
exchange 
the october contract for unleaded gasoline closed 207 cents 
higher at 5974 cents a gallon after trading as high as 6020 cents 
heating oil for october delivery jumped 160 cents to 5655 cents a 
gallon other contract months also had strong gains 
an amerada spokesman said the refinery had been shut down 
saturday in preparation for hurricane hugo the refinery had been 
producing about 400000 barrels a day of gasoline distillates and 
other products most of which are used in the united states said 
the official who asked that his name not be used 
he said amerada officials traveled to the us virgin islands to 
inspect the refinery earlier in the week but that damage from the 
hurricane made communication out of st croix difficult 
amerada said despite the shutdown it planned to maintain normal 
sales arrangements with all of its customers on the mainland of the 
united states 
traders said the strength in product prices helped buoy crude oil 
prices the october contract for west texas intermediate the 
benchmark grade of us crude oil rose 8 cents to close at 1964 a 
42gallon barrel november crude rose 29 cents to 1968 and 
december jumped 32 cents to 1946 a barrel 
energy analysts said the small gains in october crude on the last 
trading day of the contract reflected the markets belief that it 
was oversold 
buyers decided they cant justify paying the price said bob 
baker an analyst with prudentialbache securities inc 
traders said the market started out relatively calm until 
gasoline prices surged early in the day on word that amerada hess 
was buying large amounts of oil and gasoline in new york and gulf of 
mexico markets to make up for the shortfall from st croix 
but some analysts said they were surprised by the strong buying 
activity given the recent buildup of inventories particularly 
gasoline 
its hard to see why we had this kind of move baker said 
the latest weekly report by the american petroleum institute 
showed gasoline stocks rose 244000 barrels in the week ended sept 
15 distillate stocks rose more than 16 million barrels while crude 
supplies fell 96 million barrels 
baker also said a department of energy report indicates that the 
st croix refinery provides only about 50000 barrels a day of 
gasoline to us markets while the rest of its production is 
composed of products such as distillates 
</TEXT>
