<TEXT>
president bush has rejected a plea by colombian 
president virgilio barco for a 1year reinstatement of a 
coffeeexport quota system that had been beneficial to colombian 
farmers the white house said 
colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74nation 
international coffee agreement to which both the united states and 
colombia belonged collapsed in july after the united states pulled 
out in a dispute over prices with coffeeproducing nations 
barco whose nation relies on coffee as a major source of export 
earnings had appealed to bush to reconsider the coffee decision and 
to support reinstating the quotas for at least one year but the 
white house said wednesday that the decision would stand 
colombias coffee earnings have slumped at the same time that the 
bush administration is seeking barcos help in cracking down on 
cocaine exports 
colombian officials have suggested they will have an even harder 
time persuading hardpressed colombian farmers to grow coffee 
instead of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip 
the agreement set quotas for member nations exports aimed at 
suporting prices of beans at 120 per pound or more some central 
american nations and others supported by the united states wanted 
larger quotas 
after suspension of the quotas in early july prices fell quickly 
to about 85 cents a pound colombia has said this will cost 500 
million a year in export revenue 
bush in a letter to barco said the united states was ready to 
negotiate for a new quota system but was unwilling to adhere to the 
nowdefunct agreement presidential press secretary marlin fitzwater 
said 
fitzwater said bushs letter was one expressing appreciation of 
the importance of coffee to the economies of colombia and other 
developing countries 
the letter fitzwater continued expressed his bushs 
disappointment that the members of the ica were unable to settle 
two fundamental problems 
the united states wanted an increase in export quotas for 
higherquality coffees enjoyed by us consumers and tough 
penalties against countries secretly selling coffee surpluses to 
eastern bloc nations at prices below those charged the united states 
president bush expresses his confidence that a lasting solution 
which is acceptable to other major members and respects market 
trends can be found fitzwater said 
bushs letter may have opened the way for negotiations on 
restoring coffee export quotas a colombian representative said 
while bush rejected barcos plea he also said the united states 
was prepared to resume discussions on quotas at any time 
possibilities for restoring the international coffee 
organizations export quota system may be explored next week at a 
weeklong session of the 74member group 
the aim will be to maintain the momentum towards an economic 
agreement for coffee that brings back export quotas nestor 
osorio colombias permanent coffee organization delegate said in 
london 
the council will look at the market situation and could set a 
timetable for negotiations he added 
coffee prices have dropped by more than 30 percent since the ico 
export quota system was suspended on july 4 and prices touched a 
14year low of less than 67 cents per pound last month allowing for 
inflation coffee is now at its lowest level since the 1920s 
</TEXT>
