<TEXT>
west coast retailers have fared better than their 
east coast rivals this year and sales at chain stores in oilpatch 
states have grown faster than elsewhere in the country according to 
a new report 
department stores and discounters in the el paso texas 
metropolitan area posted the best sales gain for the first half of 
1989 while akron ohio retailers suffered the worst decline 
these were among the findings in a regional retail sales report 
based on results from 6000 stores with at least 25 employees each 
in the 125 largest us metropolitan areas the stores account for 
110 billion in annual sales 
the retailers which regularly submit sales figures to the us 
census bureau include such national chains as sears roebuck and 
co k mart corp and jc penney co inc mass merchants and 
department stores 
using data collected by the census bureau the international 
council of shopping centers is compiling a new monthly report that 
complements other government retail sales publications the premier 
issue released wednesday covered sales for june and the first 6 
months of 1989 
ike lagnado director of research for the shopping center trade 
group said the report indicates a regions health because consumer 
spending at general merchandise stores is a key element of economic 
activity 
nationwide consumer spending accounts for about twothirds of 
economic activity 
walter loeb a retail industry analyst at morgan stanley amp co 
said at a news conference that the new reports will help analysts 
determine store traffic trends and sales momentum which are crucial 
factors in assessing a retailers prospects 
according to the report for january through june the west south 
central or oil patch area of the country including parts of 
texas louisana arkansas and oklahoma had a sales gain of 112 
percent for the first half from the corresponding 1988 period 
the increase was by far the best of any region and compared with 
a national median increase of 45 percent 
since the oildominated economies have suffered through an 
extended widespread economic contraction a recent turnaround has 
apparently been sufficient to usher in a wave of consumer 
spending the report read 
the west had a 63 percent sales gain in the first half of 1989 
on the east coast the south atlantic states showed a growth rate of 
only 13 percent and the new england states trailed all other 
divisions within geographic regions with a 26 percent drop in 
sales 
in the midwest the report said department store sales rose 43 
percent in the first six months of the year from a year earlier but 
accelerated in the second quarter posting a rise of 53 percent 
among specific metropolitan areas el paso had a sales rise of 
187 percent in the first half of 1989 to lead gainers while akron 
sales fell by 8 percent to lead the decliners 
