the former head of g heileman brewing co says 
he is discouraged by the companys troubles since it was acquired by 
australian alan bond but he declined to speculate whether the 
countrys fifthlargest brewer might be sold again 
its unfortunate russell cleary said in a telephone 
interview from la crosse wis where heileman is based i 
certainly hope they get their act straightened out for the sake of 
the employees 
cleary said he would not speculate on whether heileman might be 
sold a spokesman for heileman referred calls to bonds headquarters 
in australia but officials there could not be reached for comment 
its a tough business and he has an enormous amount of debt 
cleary said we didnt have that debt 
through a series of acquisitions cleary built heileman into a 
national power before it was bought by bond in 1987 for about 13 
billion 
but the purchase of heileman has contributed to bonds mounting 
debts which reportedly exceed 4 billion on tuesday bond 
announced he was selling half of his brewery empire to new zealands 
lion nathan ltd for more than 760 million 
under the transaction lion nathan will buy a 50 percent interest 
in and management of bond corps swan tooheys and castlemaine 
breweries in australia and the groups hotel and associated liquor 
interests 
bond said in a statement that the brewery deal was another 
positive step in the restructuring and strategic refocusing of his 
group he said it would create a formidable brewing alliance in 
the region aimed at the pacific as well as asia 
under the proposal the brewing assets will be folded into a new 
joint venture company australian breweries pty ltd equally owned 
by bond corp and lion nathan 
bond deferred for 12 months any decision to part with heileman 
analysts say however bond is bound to lose money whether he 
sells heileman or decides to keep it 
heileman today is to some extent painted in a corner said 
robert weinberg a professor of marketing management at washington 
university in st louis 
the question is whether you operate it and bleed a little or 
take a big hit and move on said john collopy an industry analyst 
and chairman of the milwaukee investment firm cleary gull reiland 
mcdevitt amp collopy inc 
while the overall beer market has stagnated heilemans share has 
eroded falling from a high of 94 percent in 1983 to a current 
level of about 7 percent industry observers say heileman was worth 
far below 13 billion when it was sold and bond would have a hard 
time finding a buyer 
youre not getting anyone to pay 13 billion for the 
breweries said ben steinman associate publisher of beer 
marketers insights an industry newsletter 
analysts point out that heilemans sales started to slip before 
the company was sold but cleary was able to keep the company 
efficient and profitable 
his helmsmanship helped hold it together better than anyone 
could collopy said when you lose that the underlying softness 
got exaggerated 
