immunex corp on thursday announced a plan that 
will transform it from a researchdominated firm in medical 
biotechnology into a conventional pharmaceutical company 
the 8yearold company based in seattle said it would achieve 
the transition primarily by reacquiring rights to sell 
immunexdeveloped products in the united states in return its 
business partners will get rights to some other immunex products 
primarily for overseas distribution 
immunexs plan will require the company to build a sales staff 
from scratch but it should permit it to keep more of the profits 
from its work said joseph edelman an analyst at labe simpson amp co 
overall i think its an aggressive strategy edelman said 
in overthecounter trading thursday immunex stock fell 50 cents 
to 1650 
immunex uses genesplicing and other biotechnology techniques to 
create products for medical treatment mainly products that either 
promote or inhibit the activity of the immune system 
products that are being tested on people in governmentsupervised 
trials include ones for cancer therapy wound healing and protection 
of bone marrow from the harmful effects of radiation therapy and 
chemotherapy 
the biggest threat to immunex is that other companies developing 
products in the same field could challenge its patent position 
edelman said 
at the end of 1988 immunex had marketing rights for only two of 
its own products after the changes announced thursday some of 
which occurred earlier this year it will have rights to more than a 
dozen 
like many small biotech companies immunex had given marketing 
rights for its products to other companies in exchange for research 
funding and help in manufacturing even after the deals other 
companies will retain foreign marketing rights for many 
immunexrelated products 
immunexs partners include eastman kodak co west germanys 
behringwerke ag and syntex corp 
